The frustration you're feeling makes sense because regex loops are indeed inefficient for bulk replacements, and that's exactly why the aho-corasick crate exists—it builds an automaton to match multiple patterns simultaneously in a single linear scan over the text.

Your misconception is assuming that simply calling find_iter on each pattern sequentially will work efficiently; that approach re-scans the string for every pattern, which defeats the purpose of bulk processing. The real issue isn't just syntax but understanding how the automaton handles overlapping matches and backtracking.

Here's what you should do: use MatchFinder to iterate through all occurrences in one pass, then collect replacements without modifying the string until after scanning completes. This avoids the O(n*m) cost by ensuring each character is visited once regardless of pattern count:
let content = String::from("error: bad config\nwarning: missing key
debug: ok");
let mut patterns = Vec::new();
patterns.push("bad".to_string());
patterns.push("missing".to_string());

let mut replacements = HashMap::new();
let matcher = AhoCorasick::new(&patterns);
let mut match_iter = MatchFinder::new().matches(&matcher, &content);
for (start, end) in match_iter { let replacement = "ERROR".to_string(); replacements.insert(*start as usize..*end as usize, replacement); }

Finally, apply the collected replacements in reverse order to preserve indices: for (start, end) in replacements.iter() {
let content.replace_range(start, end, &replacement);
}
The key insight is that aho-corasick handles overlapping matches correctly, so you don't need to manually manage edge cases. This approach scales well even with hundreds of patterns.
